SIMPLE: slam
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Slam
<hw>Slam</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Slammed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Slamming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Of Scand. origin; cf. Icel.
<ets>slamra</ets>, <ets>slambra</ets>, <ets>sl<?/ma</ets>, Norw.
<ets>slemba</ets>, <ets>slemma</ets>, dial. Sw.
<ets>sl⟦aum⟧mma</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To shut with force and a
loud noise; to bang; <as>as, he <ex>slammed</ex> the
door</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To put in or on some place with force and loud
noise; -- usually with <xex>down</xex>; <as>as, to <ex>slam</ex> a trunk
down on the pavement</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To strike with some implement with force; hence, to
beat or cuff.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To strike down; to slaughter.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To defeat (opponents at cards) by winning all the
tricks of a deal or a hand.</def> <rj><au>Hoyle.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To slam to</b></col>, <cd>to shut or close with a
slam.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧He <xex>slammed to</xex> the door.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>W. D.
Howells.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slam</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Slam
<hw>Slam</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To come or swing against something,
or to shut, with sudden force so as to produce a shock and noise;
<as>as, a door or shutter <ex>slams</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slam</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Slam
<hw>Slam</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of one who, or
that which, slams.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The shock and noise produced in slamming.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>slam</qex> and the scowl were lost upon Sam.</q>
<rj><qau>Dickens.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Card Playing)</fld> <def>Winning all the tricks of
a deal (called, in bridge, <col><b>grand slam</b></col>, the winning of
all but one of the thirteen tricks being called a <col><b>little
slam</b></col> or <col><b>small slam</b></col>).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The refuse of alum works.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slam-bang</ent>⟦br⟧
